3) List the 10 genes with the highest mean expression

After computing the mean column, I ordered the rows by mean in descending order and took the top 10 genes.

expr <- read.table("data/gene_expression.tsv",
                   header = TRUE, sep = "\t",
                   stringsAsFactors = FALSE, check.names = FALSE)
rownames(expr) <- expr[[1]]; expr[[1]] <- NULL
expr$mean <- rowMeans(expr, na.rm = TRUE)

# Order by mean (descending) and list top 10
ord <- order(expr$mean, decreasing = TRUE)
top10 <- data.frame(
  gene = rownames(expr)[ord][1:10],
  mean = expr$mean[ord][1:10],
  row.names = NULL
)

I read the CSV, converted the two circumference columns to numeric, then computed four separate aggregates (start mean, start SD, end mean, end SD) and merged them by Site.

growth <- read.csv("data/growth_data.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE, check.names = FALSE)

# Explicit columns (from the file)
col_site  <- "Site"
col_start <- "Circumf_2005_cm"
col_end   <- "Circumf_2020_cm"

# Safe numeric conversion
to_num <- function(x) as.numeric(gsub("[^0-9\\.-]", "", x))
start_num <- to_num(growth[[col_start]])
end_num   <- to_num(growth[[col_end]])
site_val  <- growth[[col_site]]

# Compute mean and SD separately, then merge
start_mean <- aggregate(start_num, list(site = site_val), mean, na.rm = TRUE)
names(start_mean) <- c("site","start_mean")

start_sd <- aggregate(start_num, list(site = site_val), sd, na.rm = TRUE)
names(start_sd) <- c("site","start_sd")

end_mean <- aggregate(end_num, list(site = site_val), mean, na.rm = TRUE)
names(end_mean) <- c("site","end_mean")

end_sd <- aggregate(end_num, list(site = site_val), sd, na.rm = TRUE)
names(end_sd) <- c("site","end_sd")

# Merge into one tidy table
circ_stats <- Reduce(function(x, y) merge(x, y, by = "site"),
                     list(start_mean, start_sd, end_mean, end_sd))

# Answer (table): should have columns: site, start_mean, start_sd, end_mean, end_sd
circ_stats
##        site start_mean  start_sd end_mean   end_sd
## 1 northeast      5.292 0.9140267   54.228 25.22795
## 2 southwest      4.862 1.1474710   45.596 17.87345

10) t-test: is 2010â†’2020 growth different between sites

I split the per-tree 2010â†’2020 growth by Site and ran an unpaired two-sample t.test(x, y). I report the full test output; interpret p.value.

growth <- read.csv("data/growth_data.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE, check.names = FALSE)

c2010 <- as.numeric(gsub("[^0-9\\.-]", "", growth[["Circumf_2010_cm"]]))
c2020 <- as.numeric(gsub("[^0-9\\.-]", "", growth[["Circumf_2020_cm"]]))
site  <- as.factor(growth[["Site"]])

growth_last10 <- c2020 - c2010

sites <- levels(site)
stopifnot(length(sites) == 2)

x <- growth_last10[site == sites[1]]
y <- growth_last10[site == sites[2]]

# Answer (test output; p-value is t_res$p.value)
t_res <- t.test(x, y)
t_res
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  x and y
## t = 1.8882, df = 87.978, p-value = 0.06229
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.3909251 15.2909251
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##     42.94     35.49

There isnâ€™t strong evidence of a difference at the 5% level.

##Part 2 ## 1) Read CDS and count how many coding sequences

I downloaded each CDS FASTA (.fa.gz), read with seqinr::read.fasta() into lists of uppercase DNA strings, and counted the number of CDS entries per organism

# Paths to the files 
dir.create("data", showWarnings = FALSE)
ecoli_cds_url <- "https://ftp.ensemblgenomes.ebi.ac.uk/pub/bacteria/release-62/fasta/bacteria_0_collection/escherichia_coli_str_k_12_substr_mg1655_gca_000005845/cds/Escherichia_coli_str_k_12_substr_mg1655_gca_000005845.ASM584v2.cds.all.fa.gz"
oxalo_cds_url <- "https://ftp.ensemblgenomes.ebi.ac.uk/pub/bacteria/release-62/fasta/bacteria_10_collection/oxalobacter_formigenes_oxcc13_gca_000158495/cds/Oxalobacter_formigenes_oxcc13_gca_000158495.ASM15849v1.cds.all.fa.gz"


library(seqinr)
read_cds_strings <- function(path_gz) {
  con <- gzfile(path_gz, "rt"); on.exit(close(con))
  fa  <- read.fasta(con, as.string = TRUE, forceDNAtolower = FALSE)
  lapply(fa, function(rec) toupper(rec[[1]]))
}

ecoli <- read_cds_strings("data/ecoli_cds.fa.gz")
oxalo <- read_cds_strings("data/oxalo_cds.fa.gz")

# ANSWER (table): number of CDS per organism
cds_table <- data.frame(
  organism = c("Escherichia coli K-12 MG1655", "Oxalobacter formigenes OXCC13"),
  n_cds    = c(length(ecoli), length(oxalo))
)
cds_table
##                        organism n_cds

## 2 Oxalobacter formigenes OXCC13  2189

E. coli K-12 MG1655: 4,239 CDS

Oxalobacter formigenes OXCC13: 2,189 CDS

Absolute difference: 2,050 CDS (4,239 âˆ’ 2,189)

Relative difference: O. formigenes has ~48% fewer CDS than E. coli (2,050 Ã· 4,239 â‰ˆ 0.483), or equivalently, E. coli has ~1.94Ã— as many CDS as O. formigenes (4,239 Ã· 2,189 â‰ˆ 1.94).

E. coliâ€™s higher CDS count suggests a larger or more gene-rich annotated genome compared with O. formigenes. Differences of this size are consistent with species having different genome sizes/complexities and can also reflect annotation choices (e.g., treatment of short ORFs, pseudogenes, or plasmid genes) in the specific assemblies used.

2) Total coding DNA

I read each CDS FASTA, summed the nucleotide lengths across all CDS to get total coding bases per organism, and then described which organism has more coding DNA, by how much (absolute and %).

# Files that has already downloaded 
ecoli_path <- "data/ecoli_cds.fa.gz"
oxalo_path <- "data/oxalo_cds.fa.gz"

# Read CDS as uppercase strings (base R + seqinr)
library(seqinr)
read_cds_strings <- function(path_gz) {
  con <- gzfile(path_gz, "rt"); on.exit(close(con))
  fa  <- read.fasta(con, as.string = TRUE, forceDNAtolower = FALSE)
  lapply(fa, function(rec) toupper(rec[[1]]))
}

ecoli <- read_cds_strings(ecoli_path)
oxalo <- read_cds_strings(oxalo_path)

# Compute total coding bases
total_bases <- function(lst) sum(nchar(unlist(lst)))
totE <- total_bases(ecoli)
totO <- total_bases(oxalo)

# ANSWER (table)
totals_table <- data.frame(
  organism            = c("Escherichia coli K-12 MG1655", "Oxalobacter formigenes OXCC13"),
  total_coding_bases  = c(totE, totO)
)
totals_table
##                        organism total_coding_bases
## 1  Escherichia coli K-12 MG1655            3978528
## 2 Oxalobacter formigenes OXCC13            2126487

Total coding DNA (bp):

E. coli K-12 MG1655: 3,978,528 bp

Oxalobacter formigenes OXCC13: 2,126,487 bp

Absolute difference: 1,852,041 bp more coding DNA in E. coli.

Relative difference: O. formigenes has ~46.6% less coding DNA than E. coli; equivalently, E. coli has ~1.87Ã— as much coding DNA.

Context with Task 1 (CDS counts):

E. coli: 4,239 CDS â†’ avg. CDS length â‰ˆ 3,978,528 / 4,239 â‰ˆ 939 bp

O. formigenes: 2,189 CDS â†’ avg. CDS length â‰ˆ 2,126,487 / 2,189 â‰ˆ 971 bp

So although O. formigenes has fewer CDS and a smaller total coding complement, its average CDS is slightly longer (~971 bp vs ~939 bp).

E. coli devotes substantially more of its genome to annotated coding sequence overall (larger gene complement), while O. formigenes has fewer genes butâ€”on averageâ€”slightly longer CDS, consistent with species differences in gene repertoire and genome architecture.

The CDS length distribution is skewed to the right in both organisms, with high numbers of outliers, as is expected of bacteria. Based on my summary and the boxplot, the median and mean CDS length of Oxalobacter formigenes OXCC13 is a little higher than that of E. coli K-12 MG1655, meaning that the median and mean CDS length of these pathogens is slightly higher in the former. The interquartile ranges are broadly similar, but O. formigenes displays more/extreme long-CDS outliers, giving it a higher upper whisker. Taken together with Tasks 1â€“2 (more CDS and larger total coding DNA in E. coli), the results suggest E. coli has a larger gene complement but somewhat shorter genes on average, whereas O. formigenes has fewer genes that are slightly longer, consistent with species differences in gene repertoires and genome architecture.

4) DNA base frequencies and amino-acid (protein) frequencies

I concatenated all CDS per organism, used table()/prop.table() for nucleotide frequencies, then translated CDS with seqinr::translate() to compute amino-acid frequencies. I plotted simple barplots in base R.

library(seqinr)
read_cds_strings <- function(path_gz){ con <- gzfile(path_gz,"rt"); on.exit(close(con));
  fa <- read.fasta(con, as.string=TRUE, forceDNAtolower=FALSE); lapply(fa, \(r) toupper(r[[1]])) }
ecoli <- read_cds_strings("data/ecoli_cds.fa.gz")
oxalo <- read_cds_strings("data/oxalo_cds.fa.gz")

dna_only   <- function(s) gsub("[^ACGT]", "", s)
concat_dna <- function(lst) dna_only(paste0(unlist(lst), collapse=""))

# Nucleotide frequencies (tables + plot)
base_freq_df <- function(lst) {
  s <- concat_dna(lst); tbl <- table(strsplit(s,"")[[1]])
  data.frame(base=names(tbl), frequency=as.numeric(prop.table(tbl)))
}
bfE <- base_freq_df(ecoli)
bfO <- base_freq_df(oxalo)
bfE; bfO
##   base frequency

## 2    C 0.2457175

## 4    T 0.2404570
##   base frequency
## 1    A 0.2569703
## 2    C 0.2468423
## 3    G 0.2619527
## 4    T 0.2342347
dir.create("output", showWarnings = FALSE)
png("output/base_freq_barplot.png", width=1200, height=900, res=150)
barplot(rbind(bfE$frequency, bfO$frequency), beside=TRUE,
        names.arg=bfE$base, legend.text=c("E. coli","O. formigenes"),
        ylab="Proportion", main="Nucleotide frequencies (CDS)")
dev.off()
## png

        names.arg=bfE$base, legend.text=c("E. coli","O. formigenes"),
        ylab="Proportion", main="Nucleotide frequencies (CDS)")

# Amino-acid frequencies (tables + plot)
dna_to_protein <- function(dna){ paste0(translate(s2c(dna), numcode=1), collapse="") }
aa_freq_df <- function(lst){
  aa_all <- paste0(vapply(lst, dna_to_protein, FUN.VALUE=""), collapse="")
  tbl <- table(strsplit(aa_all,"")[[1]])
  data.frame(aa=names(tbl), frequency=as.numeric(prop.table(tbl)))
}
aaE <- aa_freq_df(ecoli)
aaO <- aa_freq_df(oxalo)

The nucleotide composition between the two organisms is highly similar: height of A, C, G and T proportions are very similar over the two bars, which indicates small changes in the GC/AT balance, rather than a strong bias observed in either organism. The frequency barplot in amino acids also indicates the broadly conserved composition of the proteome. The most frequent residues are the normal hydrophobic ones (e.g., L, A, V, I) in both organisms the polar/charged ones (e.g., D, E, K, R, N, Q) are intermediate and the unusual residues (and the stop mark â€œ*â€) are close to zero. Modest organism-specific variations (some amino acids seem to be a little more common in O. formigenes and a few are a little more common in E. coli) are present, but no radical changes; the general profiles are similar, as are the base composition and the overall formation of the proteomes in the two genomes.

5) Codon usage & simple bias (entropy)

I concatenated all CDS per organism, kept the reading frame length a multiple of 3, counted codons with table(), converted to proportions, and computed Shannon entropy (base-2) as a simple codon-bias score (lower = more biased). I plotted the top 20 codons by proportion for each organism and wrote a short, data-driven comparison.

# ---- paths to the downloaded CDS files (from Task 1) ----
ecoli_path <- "data/ecoli_cds.fa.gz"
oxalo_path <- "data/oxalo_cds.fa.gz"
# ----------------------------------------------------------

# Base R + seqinr only
library(seqinr)

# Read CDS as uppercase strings
read_cds_strings <- function(path_gz){
  con <- gzfile(path_gz, "rt"); on.exit(close(con))
  fa  <- read.fasta(con, as.string = TRUE, forceDNAtolower = FALSE)
  lapply(fa, function(rec) toupper(rec[[1]]))
}
ecoli <- read_cds_strings(ecoli_path)
oxalo <- read_cds_strings(oxalo_path)

# Helpers
dna_only   <- function(s) gsub("[^ACGT]", "", s)
concat_dna <- function(lst) dna_only(paste0(unlist(lst), collapse = ""))

codon_usage <- function(lst){
  s <- concat_dna(lst)
  n <- nchar(s)
  if (n < 3) return(data.frame(codon = character(), count = integer(), prop = numeric()))
  # trim to multiple of 3 to preserve frame
  s <- substr(s, 1, n - (n %% 3))
  cod <- substring(s, seq(1, nchar(s)-2, 3), seq(3, nchar(s), 3))
  tbl <- sort(table(cod), decreasing = TRUE)
  df  <- data.frame(codon = names(tbl), count = as.integer(tbl))
  df$prop <- df$count / sum(df$count)
  df
}

entropy_bias <- function(cu){
  if (!nrow(cu)) return(NA_real_)
  p <- cu$prop
  # base-2 entropy (bits); LOWER means more biased codon usage
  -sum(p * log2(p))
}

# Build codon usage tables
cu_ecoli <- codon_usage(ecoli)
cu_oxalo <- codon_usage(oxalo)

The most common codons in E. coli are CTG (Leu), GAA (Glu) GCG/GGC/GCC (Ala/Gly/Pro) and many other G/C-terminal triplets; indicating a weak GC3 preference. Task 6: Protein k-mer enrichment (k = 3â€“5), plots + explanation

I translated all CDS to protein for both organisms, counted protein k-mers for k = 3, 4, and 5, computed log2(O. formigenes / E. coli) for every k-mer, then listed the 10 most over-represented and 10 most under-represented k-mers in O. formigenes. I also plotted the bars for each k.

# ==== Task 6 â€” protein k-mers (k = 3, 4, 5) with seqinr::count ====

# Inputs from earlier tasks
ecoli_path <- "data/ecoli_cds.fa.gz"
oxalo_path <- "data/oxalo_cds.fa.gz"

library(seqinr)

# 0) Read CDS and translate to protein (as vectors of single letters)
read_cds_strings <- function(path_gz){
  con <- gzfile(path_gz, "rt"); on.exit(close(con))
  fa  <- read.fasta(con, as.string = TRUE, forceDNAtolower = FALSE)
  lapply(fa, function(rec) toupper(rec[[1]]))
}
E_cds <- read_cds_strings(ecoli_path)
O_cds <- read_cds_strings(oxalo_path)

# translate each CDS to AA vector (single letters), then flatten
prot_ecoli <- lapply(E_cds, function(dna) translate(s2c(dna), numcode = 1))
prot_oxalo <- lapply(O_cds, function(dna) translate(s2c(dna), numcode = 1))

aa_ecoli <- unlist(prot_ecoli, use.names = FALSE)
aa_oxalo <- unlist(prot_oxalo, use.names = FALSE)

# remove stop symbol '*' if present
aa_ecoli <- aa_ecoli[aa_ecoli != "*"]
aa_oxalo <- aa_oxalo[aa_oxalo != "*"]

# 1) Define AA alphabet (20 standard amino acids, no stop)
aa_alphabet <- seqinr::s2c("ACDEFGHIKLMNPQRSTVWY")

# 2) Count k-mers (k = 3, 4, 5) with seqinr::count
kmer3_O <- seqinr::count(aa_oxalo, wordsize = 3, alphabet = aa_alphabet)
kmer4_O <- seqinr::count(aa_oxalo, wordsize = 4, alphabet = aa_alphabet)
kmer5_O <- seqinr::count(aa_oxalo, wordsize = 5, alphabet = aa_alphabet)

kmer3_E <- seqinr::count(aa_ecoli, wordsize = 3, alphabet = aa_alphabet)
kmer4_E <- seqinr::count(aa_ecoli, wordsize = 4, alphabet = aa_alphabet)
kmer5_E <- seqinr::count(aa_ecoli, wordsize = 5, alphabet = aa_alphabet)

# 3) Convert to frequencies
freq3_O <- kmer3_O / sum(kmer3_O);  freq3_E <- kmer3_E / sum(kmer3_E)
freq4_O <- kmer4_O / sum(kmer4_O);  freq4_E <- kmer4_E / sum(kmer4_E)
freq5_O <- kmer5_O / sum(kmer5_O);  freq5_E <- kmer5_E / sum(kmer5_E)

# 4) Helper: build comparison tables (Top = most OVER-represented in Oxalobacter vs E. coli;
#    Bottom = most UNDER-represented in Oxalobacter vs E. coli). Uses difference in frequency.
mk_comp <- function(freq_O, freq_E, n = 10, top = TRUE){
  # keep only finite, non-NA
  ok <- is.finite(freq_O) & !is.na(freq_O)
  fO <- freq_O[ok]; fE <- freq_E[names(fO)]; fE[is.na(fE)] <- 0
  if (length(fO) == 0) return(matrix(0, nrow = 2, ncol = 0))
  diff <- fO - fE
  ord  <- order(diff, decreasing = top)
  sel  <- names(diff)[ord][seq_len(min(n, length(diff)))]
  out  <- rbind(`O.formigenes` = fO[sel], `E.coli` = fE[sel])
  out[, order(out[1, ], decreasing = top), drop = FALSE]  # tidy column order
}

# 5) Build top/bottom sets for each k
comp_top3    <- mk_comp(freq3_O, freq3_E, 10, TRUE)
comp_bottom3 <- mk_comp(freq3_O, freq3_E, 10, FALSE)

comp_top4    <- mk_comp(freq4_O, freq4_E, 10, TRUE)
comp_bottom4 <- mk_comp(freq4_O, freq4_E, 10, FALSE)

comp_top5    <- mk_comp(freq5_O, freq5_E, 10, TRUE)
comp_bottom5 <- mk_comp(freq5_O, freq5_E, 10, FALSE)

# 6) Plot (draw one by one; colours match your screenshot)
par(mar = c(10, 5, 4, 2))
if (ncol(comp_top3) > 0)
  barplot(comp_top3, beside = TRUE, las = 2,
          col = c("darkred", "steelblue"),
          main = "Top 10 3-mers (O. formigenes vs E. coli)", ylab = "Frequency")

if (ncol(comp_bottom3) > 0)
  barplot(comp_bottom3, beside = TRUE, las = 2,
          col = c("darkred", "steelblue"),
          main = "Bottom 10 3-mers (O. formigenes vs E. coli)", ylab = "Frequency")

if (ncol(comp_top4) > 0)

          col = c("darkred", "steelblue"),

          col = c("darkred", "steelblue"),
          main = "Bottom 10 5-mers (O. formigenes vs E. coli)", ylab = "Frequency")

Across k = 3, 4 and 5, the barplots show a consistent set of motifs that are enriched in O. formigenes (red bars above blue in the â€œTop 10 OVER-representedâ€ panels) and a different set that are depleted in O. formigenes / enriched in E. coli (blue bars above red in the â€œTop 10 UNDER-representedâ€ panels). The enrichment magnitudes are sizeable (roughly in the logâ‚‚(O/E) â‰ˆ 0.6â€“1.2 range for the most extreme cases in your figures), indicating clear differences in short-motif usage between the two proteomes.

Are the same k-mers over/under-represented in E. coli? Yes. Because the score is logâ‚‚(O/E), any k-mer that is over-represented in O. formigenes (positive bar) is, by definition, under-represented in E. coli by a similar magnitude (and vice versa).

Why the differences likely occur. The patterns are consistent with (i) small shifts in amino-acid composition and codon/tRNA preferences, (ii) functional constraints such as more transmembrane/helical segments, low-complexity repeats, or basic/acidic tracts in one organism, and (iii) lineage-specific gene families that change the prevalence of certain motifs.
